# Guardrails

## API Rate Limits
- **Confluence**: Max 3 page reads per turn. If you need more, ask user first.
- **Jira**: Max 5 JQL searches per turn. Use efficient queries (filter by project, date, component).
- **Slack**: Max 3 message searches per turn.
- **Never** make unbounded searches (e.g., "all tickets in PRODOPS"). Always scope by date, component, or keyword.

---

## PHI / PII Protection — OUTPUT SIDE
*(These rules govern what the bot writes to Jira, Slack, Confluence, etc.)*

- NEVER include patient names, SSNs, DOBs, or health information in ticket comments.
- If a ticket contains PHI/PII, flag it: "⚠️ This ticket may contain PHI/PII. Flagged for manual review."
- NEVER copy raw log contents that might contain PHI into comments.

---

## PHI / PII Protection — INPUT SIDE (Attachment Pipeline)
*(These rules govern what the bot reads from attachments BEFORE sending to the AI model.)*

> **Why this matters**: The HIPAA exposure occurs the moment PHI reaches the AI model —
> not when it appears in output. These rules prevent PHI from ever entering the model's
> context window.

**Rule I-1 — Never read quarantined files.**
If `_manifest.md` marks a file as `🚨 QUARANTINED`, do NOT open, read, or reference
its content. The content has been deleted by the PHI scanner. Include this note:
> "⚠️ Attachment `{filename}` was quarantined — PHI detected ({types}). Human review required."

**Rule I-2 — Never read blocked files.**
If `_manifest.md` marks a file as `🚫 BLOCKED` (phi_risk type or phi-risk filename),
do NOT attempt to download, read, or access it by any means. Include this note:
> "⚠️ Attachment `{filename}` was blocked (high PHI-risk). Review directly in Jira."

**Rule I-3 — Never bypass fetch.py.**
ALL attachment downloads MUST go through `scripts/attachment_reader/fetch.py`.
Do NOT use curl, wget, direct Jira REST API calls, or any other method to download
attachment content. The PHI pipeline only runs through fetch.py.

**Rule I-4 — Apply first-10-lines check on all text files.**
Even for files marked ✅ Clean, read the first 10 lines before proceeding. If you
observe SSNs (###-##-####), MRNs, DOBs, patient/member names or IDs, or insurance
policy numbers — STOP reading immediately and flag the file for manual review.

**Rule I-5 — Image PHI discipline.**
You MAY view images and screenshots. However, do NOT describe, transcribe, or quote
any patient-identifiable information visible in the image (names, MRNs, DOBs, account
numbers in UI fields). If PHI is visible, note:
> "Screenshot contains potentially identifiable information — redacted per HIPAA policy."

**Rule I-6 — PDF extracted text handling.**
Treat `*_extracted.txt` files (PDF text extractions) the same as text files.
Apply Rule I-4 (first-10-lines check) before reading in full.

**Rule I-7 — Ticket description and comments.**
The Jira ticket description and comment fields may also contain PHI. Do NOT include
raw description or comment text in any output. Summarize or paraphrase only.
If the description contains obvious PHI patterns (SSN, MRN, DOB), flag the ticket
for manual review and do not process it further.

**Rule I-8 — Always report PHI findings.**
When attachments are processed, always include a PHI Protection Summary in your output:
```
## Attachment PHI Protection Summary
- Total attachments: N
- Readable by agent: N
- Blocked (pre-download): N  [filenames]
- Quarantined (PHI scan): N  [filenames + PHI types]
- Action required: [files needing human review, or "None"]
```

